profile_positions.description:
Responsible for the coordination and management of this EU REC (2014-2020)-funded project to ensure the successful delivery of all project work packages, deliverables and activities on child rights and child participation, implemented across 7 European countries. Responsibilities included:
• Regular, mid-term and final reporting to EU funding authorities and UNICEF NatComs and PFP on project performance across all partners and activities in the project;
• Contributing to the development, drafting and design of 5 international UNICEF toolkits on the Child Rights Schools model, including rights-based child participation, piloting the CRS model, scaling-up the CRS model, M&E of the CRS model and school self-assessment toolkit of children’s rights.
• Communication lead between internal and external stakeholders;
• Coordination of the External Mid-Term and Final Project Evaluation;
• Knowledge management;
• Coordination with financial departments to ensure accurate and timely expenditure and delivery of financial reporting;
• Manage overall data quality in relation to the project; proactively testing, cleaning and updating data to ensure information is up to date, accurate and GDPR compliant.

Managing the Peace and Human Security Framework Agreement, awarded by Swedish International Development Cooperation (Sida). This programme provides support to peace- and state-building, to inclusive dialogues and mediation processes, to strengthening the influence of women and girls and their meaningful participation in peace processes, to protection of children in conflict and in peace, to mine action, SALW reduction, and to transitional justice. Tasks include: 
•	Supporting effective delivery of call-off assignments through overseeing day-to-day logistical, procedural and financial aspects;
•	Ensuring that all Standard Operating Procedures are being adhered to across the Consortium; 
•	Assessing financial viability and possible logistical or security-related concerns of the call-off assignments;
•	Project management: including maintaining client and partner relations, financial and strategic management, human resource management, monitoring of overall progress of the Framework Contract, and practical and administrative programme support.

Managing the EU-funded 'Results Oriented Monitoring (ROM) System for External Aid Interventions: Lot 1 – ROM for Asia and Pacific, Latin America, Caribbean' - project, awarded by European Commission DG Devco. This project which aims to improve the sustainable performance of EU-funded interventions in Asia, the Pacific, Latin America and the Caribbean by strengthening design, monitoring and evaluation systems at intervention and institutional level. Tasks include:
•	Monitoring of the project progress, including development of budgets; 
•	Recruitment and contracting of about 50 international and local experts;
•	Establishing and maintaining partner relations: daily collaboration with the ROM Team in Brussels to ensure efficient project implementation; 
•	Practical, financial and administrative project support, e.g. approving timesheets and invoices, accurate information distribution, compliance to donor procedures etc.

• Preparing and writing expressions of interests (EoIs) and proposals for various donors, e.g. European Commission (EU), Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Swedish International Development Cooperation (Sida) and World Bank. This included technical assistance and M&E projects in the field of civil society, peace, human security, migration, job creation, private sector development, food security and financial management in Africa, Asia and Latin America. Tasks included: recruitment of experts, consortium building, compliance to donor regulations and priorities (e.g. PRAG),  and drafting of budgets; 
• Detecting upcoming opportunities with Ecorys’ key clients through market research and maintaining strong relationships;
• Board member of ‘Young Ecorys”: presenting the voice of fellow young colleagues (<35 years) to the Board of Management of Ecorys and organising events and workshops for this young Ecoryians to exchange experiences.

Contributed to the study on ‘Volunteer Trips from the Netherlands with Children in Residential Institutions Abroad’, commissioned by the Netherlands Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MFA). This study investigated the scope of volunteer trips, the diverse actors that play a role in volunteering tourism, as well as the flows of money involved. Specific attention was paid to volunteer work in projects where the residential care of children is a central point of focus. Tasks included:
•	Brainstorming and development of the research design, in close collaboration with the Steering Committee, chaired by the Netherlands MFA;
•	Desk study of existing literature on child rights’, residential care institutions and volunteer tourism; 
•	Design, collection and analysis of quantitative (surveys with volunteer organisations, experts, policy makers, NGOs) and qualitative data collection (15 – 20 interviews and four round table discussion groups with volunteer organisations, NGOs, child rights experts and policy makers in the Netherlands and abroad);
•	Drafting parts of the final report.

Responsible for development and implementation of coherent Dutch foreign policy for the Sahel region. Main responsibilities:
•	Country officer Mauritania: incoming- and outgoing political affairs, maintaining excellent bilateral relations and monitoring and advising on various programs; 
•	New embassy offices in Burkina Faso and Chad: Supervised, coordinated and monitored the operationalisation of two new embassy offices; 
•	Gender in the Sahel: responsible for and provided input to assure gender mainstreaming in all projects from the Netherlands MFA in the Sahel; 
•	Parliamentary Affairs: prepared ministerial visits to the Sahel (Minister of Foreign Affairs and the Minister of Development Cooperation and International Trade), reported and drafted information for parliamentary affairs (e.g. input for EC EUTF for Africa meetings), organised multiple international events and seminars incl. high-level officials;
•	Multi-annual Sahel Strategy: contributed to the development of the Multi-annual Sahel Strategy, which involved intra- and interdepartmental coordination and brainstorming, e.g. on youth and children in the Sahel;

•	Contributed to data-driven city marketing of Amsterdam as the ideal city for both citizens, companies and tourists;
•	Supported in project- and partner management of Visitor Insight; a tool which shows an overview of tourism development in Amsterdam; 
•	Performed data management and analyses via Excel, SPSS and Modeler for the Visitors’ Inquiry Amsterdam 2016.

volunteer_experiences.description:
• Organised a 10-day dialogue seminar on “discrimination of sexual minorities” with 25 participants from Uganda, Ghana and Russia. This included recruitment of participants, preparation of the participants, and developing and facilitating several dialogue sessions;
• Trained and supervised Ugandan participants in dialogue facilitation during the follow-up seminar on “The Refugee Crisis” in Kampala, Uganda with about 15 participants from Burundi, Rwanda, South Sudan and Uganda;
• Completed ‘Dialogue Facilitation and Conflict Understanding Course’ at Nansen Dialogue Network.

A foundation fighting for accountability and transparency within international volunteer.
• Developed an evaluation instrument: “Transparency Index” to enhance transparency among Dutch volunteer tourism organisations working with children institutions abroad;
• Organised the launch of this index for stakeholders, partners, volunteer organisations and journalists in Pakhuis de Zwijger;
• Contributed to general strategical and operational management of Foundation Volunteer Correct.
